**Clinical Reasoning:**
The patient presents with classic B symptoms—unintentional weight loss, night sweats, and low-grade fever—as well as generalized lymphadenopathy, hepatosplenomegy, and pallor—all consistent with Hodgkin lymphoma. Among the listed viruses, Epstein-Barr virus (EBV) is strongly associated with both infectious mononucleosis and increased risk of developing Hodgkin lymphoma, particularly in association with splenomegaly, lymphadenopathy, and systemic symptoms. While other viruses like HHV-8 or HPV are linked to different lymphomas, EBV remains the most established link to Hodgkin lymphoma pathogenesis.

